[4] What do these HTTP status codes mean: 200, 301, 404, 500, 403?
    => 200 OK – The request was successful and the webpage loaded correctly.
       301 Moved Permanently – The webpage has been permanently moved to a new URL.
       404 Not Found – The requested webpage or resource could not be found.
       500 Internal Server Error – The server encountered an error and could not process the request.
       403 Forbidden – Access to the requested resource is denied.

[5] Explain DNS hierarchy (root, TLD, domain, subdomain) with www.google.com as an example.
  =>  Root (.) – The highest level in the DNS hierarchy, represented by a dot (.) at the end: www.google.com.
      TLD (Top-Level Domain) – com is the top-level domain.
      Domain – google is the main domain name registered under .com.
      Subdomain – www is a subdomain of google.com, used to identify a specific service or website.
       
